<section xml:id="using-the-quadratic-formula">
    <title>Using the Quadratic Formula</title>
    <subsection xml:id="solving-equations-using-the-quadratic-formula">
        <title>Solving Equations Using the Quadratic Formula</title>
    <example xml:id="solving-an-equation-with-two-real-roots">
        <title>Solving an Equation with Two Real Roots</title>

        <statement>
            <p>Solve the equation <m>4x^2 + 13x + 10 = 0</m> using the Quadratic Formula.</p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>x = -2</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>x = -\frac{5}{4}</m></p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
            <p>The equation <m>4x^2 + 13x + 10 = 0</m> can be solved by substituting <m>a = 4</m>, <m>b = 13</m>, and <m>c = 10</m> into the Quadratic Formula <m>x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}</m>.</p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x \amp= \frac{-13 \pm \sqrt{13^2 - 4(4)(10)}}{2(4)} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{-13 \pm \sqrt{169 - 160}}{8} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{-13 \pm \sqrt{9}}{8} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{-13 \pm 3}{8} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= \frac{-13 + 3}{8} \amp x\amp= \frac{-13 - 3}{8} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= \frac{-10}{8} \amp x\amp= \frac{-16}{8} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= -\frac{5}{4}\amp x\amp= -2 \\</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>Thus, the solutions are <m>x = -2</m> and <m>x = -\frac{5}{4}</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="solving-an-equation-with-one-real-root">
        <title>Solving an Equation with One Real Root</title>

        <statement>
            <p>Solve the equation <m>16x^2 + 24x + 9 = 0</m> using the Quadratic Formula.</p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
            <p><m>x = -\frac{3}{4}</m></p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
            <p>Substitute <m>a = 16</m>, <m>b = 24</m>, and <m>c = 9</m> into <m>x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}</m>.</p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x \amp= \frac{-24 \pm \sqrt{24^2 - 4(16)(9)}}{2(16)} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{-24 \pm \sqrt{576 - 576}}{32} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{-24 \pm \sqrt{0}}{32} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{-24 \pm 0}{32} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= \frac{-24}{32} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= -\frac{3}{4} \\</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>Thus, the (repeated) solution is <m>x = -\frac{3}{4}</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="solving-an-equation-with-two-complex-solutions">
        <title>Solving an Equation with Two Complex Solutions</title>

        <statement>
            <p>Solve the equation <m>x^2 - 4x + 13 = 0</m> using the Quadratic Formula.</p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
            <p><m>x = 2 \pm 3i</m></p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
            <p>Substitute <m>a = 1</m>, <m>b = -4</m>, and <m>c = 13</m> into <m>x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}</m>.</p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>x \amp= \frac{-(-4) \pm \sqrt{(-4)^2 - 4(1)(13)}}{2(1)} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{4 \pm \sqrt{16 - 52}}{2} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{4 \pm \sqrt{-36}}{2} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{4 \pm 6i}{2} \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp= \frac{4}{2}\pm\frac{6}{2}i \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= 2 \pm 3i \\</mrow>
                    <mrow>x \amp= 2 + 3i \amp x\amp= 2 - 3i \\</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>Thus, the solutions are <m>x = 2 + 3i</m> and <m>x = 2 - 3i</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>
</subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="sub-the-discriminant">
        <title>The Discriminant</title>
        <p>
            The number and types of solutions for <xref ref="solving-an-equation-with-two-real-roots"/>, <xref ref="solving-an-equation-with-one-real-root"/>, and <xref ref="solving-an-equation-with-two-complex-solutions"/> can be summarized as follows.
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The value of <m>b^2-4ac</m> for <xref ref="solving-an-equation-with-two-real-roots"/> is positive.  This gave us two, real-valued solutions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The value of <m>b^2-4ac</m> for <xref ref="solving-an-equation-with-one-real-root"/> equals zero. This gave us a unique, real-valued solution.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The value of <m>b^2-4ac</m> for <xref ref="solving-an-equation-with-two-complex-solutions"/> is negative. This gave us a pair of complex numbers that are conjugates of one another.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            The value of <m>b^2-4ac</m> is called the discriminant since it discriminates between the different types of solutions a quadratic equation can have.
        </p>
        <definition xml:id="the-discriminant">
    <title>The Discriminant</title>

    <statement>
        <p>We call the value <m>b^2 - 4ac</m> the <term>discriminant</term> of the quadratic equation.
           We denote the discriminant by the letter <m>D</m>, which gives us the equation <me>D = b^2 - 4ac</me>.</p>
        <p>In particular, the discriminant tells us the following information:</p>

        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>If <m>D &gt; 0</m>, then the quadratic equation has two distinct, real-valued solutions.</p></li>
                <li><p>If <m>D = 0</m>, then the quadratic equation has a unique, real-valued solution.</p></li>
                <li><p>If <m>D &lt; 0</m>, then the quadratic equation has a pair of complex-valued solutions that are complex conjugates of one another.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="use-the-discriminant-to-determine-the-number-and-types-of-solutions-v1">
    <title>Use the Discriminant to Determine the Number and Types of Solutions, Version 1</title>

    <statement>
        <p>Determine the number and type of solutions for the equation <m>6x^2 + x - 40 = 0</m>.</p>
    </statement>

    <answer>
        <p>Two distinct, real-valued solutions.</p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
        <p>In this case, we have <m>a = 6</m>, <m>b = 1</m>, and <m>c = -40</m>. We calculate the discriminant as follows.</p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>D \amp= b^2 - 4ac \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= (1)^2 - 4(6)(-40) \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 1 + 960 \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 961 \\</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>Since <m>D &gt; 0</m>, we have two distinct, real-valued solutions.</p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="use-the-discriminant-to-determine-the-number-and-types-of-solutions-v2">
    <title>Use the Discriminant to Determine the Number and Types of Solutions, Version 2</title>

    <statement>
        <p>Determine the number and type of solutions for the equation <m>16x^2 - 8x + 1 = 0</m>.</p>
    </statement>

    <answer>
        <p>One unique, real-valued solution.</p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
        <p>In this case, we have <m>a = 16</m>, <m>b = -8</m>, and <m>c = 1</m>. We calculate the discriminant as follows.</p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>D \amp= b^2 - 4ac \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= (-8)^2 - 4(16)(1) \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 64 - 64 \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 0 \\</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>Since <m>D = 0</m>, we have a unique, real-valued solution.</p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="use-the-discriminant-to-determine-the-number-and-types-of-solutions-v3">
    <title>Use the Discriminant to Determine the Number and Types of Solutions, Version 3</title>

    <statement>
        <p>Determine the number and type of solutions for the equation <m>x^2 - 10x + 74 = 0</m>.</p>
    </statement>

    <answer>
        <p>Two complex-valued solutions that are complex conjugates of one another.</p>
    </answer>

    <solution>
        <p>In this case, we have <m>a = 1</m>, <m>b = -10</m>, and <m>c = 74</m>. We calculate the discriminant as follows.</p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>D \amp= b^2 - 4ac \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= (-10)^2 - 4(1)(74) \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= 100 - 296 \\</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp= -196 \\</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>Since <m>D &lt; 0</m>, the equation has two complex-valued solutions that are complex conjugates of one another.</p>
    </solution>
</example>

    </subsection>
</section>
